We can create an in-memory AOI service that will receive requests
from the UAVs and update an in-memory quadtree. When a UAV updates
it's location we will remove the previous locaton from the quadtree and
assign it's new location. If we choose to extend the functionality of our
system our quadtree can hold things like object detections and we can serve
the contents of the quadtree to our client interface.
When the AOI service receives a request for a new AOI, it will enqueue this
into an in memory queue within the AOI service. If there are many idle UAVs,
we can fetch the closest UAV based upon distance. If there is a single idle
UAV we can directly assign it this task. If there are no idle UAVs we will
keep this task within the queue. Once a UAV reports that it's idle, we can
then assign that newly idle UAV with it's task.
Once an AOI has been assigned, we can update it's status, and wait for it to
start streaming data to our data streaming service. This will transition the status
Our data streaming service will handle incoming requests from our UAVs.
It will open a request for a given AOI, write it to s3, and generate a
frame catalogue that will be streamed to the users upon request.
In the future, we can also leverage this service for object detection and
updating our AOI service with classified objects. Things like tanks, cars,
We will enqueue objects for classification to our object detection service.
It will be able to take frames from our queue for classification. It will then
respond to our data streaming service with classified objects. The data streaming
service can send a request to our location service with new objects to add to our
in-memory quadtree. This data can be served to our client.
Our data streaming service should scale based upon CPU
and memory utilization. Once a UAV starts streaming to one of our services,

Our location service is now a single point of failure. We should have replication of our
in-memory quadtree across multiple instances of this service. We can have leaderless
replication across all of our instances with N/2+1 consistency requirements for reads/writes.
This will provide the most up-to-date location data available as we ensure that the majority
of our nodes have the correct data while maintaining availability in the event of failure or
When a new node comes online, it can fetch available AOIs from our database and build it's quadtree
of information while receiving incoming requests from upstream providers. This will allow it to 'catch up'
to the rest of the nodes.
